refreshment.Based on a major mixed-methods research project on dining out in England, this book offers a unique comparison of the social differences between London, Bristol and Preston from 1995 to 2015, charting the dynamic relationship between eating in and eating out. Addressing topics such as the changing domestic divisions of labour around food preparation, the variety of culinary experience for different sections of the population, and class differences in taste and the pleasures and satisfactions associated with dining out, the authors explore how the practice has evolved across the three cities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDinners and diningxSocial aspectszEngland. 0aDinners and diningxSocial aspects. 0aFood habitsxSocial aspects. 0aRestaurantsxSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Human Geography.2bisacsh  aConsumption.  aCultural omnivorousness.  aDining out.  aDomestic entertaining.  aEating in.  aEating out.  aInformalisation.  aNormalisation.  aPractice theory.  aVariety.1 aPaddock, Jessica, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aPaddock, Jessica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWarde, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWhillans, Jennifer, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWhillans, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packagez978311128248040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152613476940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526134769423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526134769/original  a978-3-11-128248-0  Manchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packageb2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles